        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-07-17T05:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-07-17T05:30:00-05:00" n="244"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d244">
                <head>244. Telegram From the Embassy in Iran to the Department of State<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d244fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1950–1954, 788.00/7–1753.
                        Secret; Security Information. Repeated to London and to Geneva for <persName
                            corresp="#p_HLW_1">Henderson</persName>. Received at 2:40 p.m. The
                        telegram is printed with redactions in <ref target="frus1952-54v10#d334">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1952–1954, vol. X, Iran,
                            1951–1954, pp. 736–737 (Document 334)</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Tehran</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1953-07-17T14:00:00+03:30">July 17, 1953, 2 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <p>116. Estimate Embassy and CAS present political trends follows.</p>
                <p>Immediate reason <persName corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName>’s precipitate
                    move eliminate present Majlis as opposition center was mounting effectiveness
                    anti-government activity such as Zohari interpellation and election <persName
                        corresp="#p_MH_1">Maki</persName> as controller <gloss target="#t_BMI_1"
                        >BMI</gloss>. Opposition was also successfully gaining control key Majlis
                    committees. Serving accelerate these events and impel <persName
                        corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName> consolidate his position urgently was
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD_1">Eisenhower</persName> letter clarifying <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> policy toward <persName corresp="#p_MM_1"
                        >Mosadeq</persName> Government.<note n="2" xml:id="d244fn2">See <ref
                            target="#d230">Document 230</ref>.</note> Letter served belie carefully
                    nursed “myth” <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> supporting <persName
                        corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName> at same time <gloss target="#t_USSR_1"
                        >USSR</gloss> “friendship” overtures appear to be for moment at least
                    nothing more than willingness adjust frontier problems. With bankruptcy foreign
                    policy thus exposed Prime Minister faced Majlis interpellation this subject and
                    exposure government’s unauthorized increase note issue by <persName
                        corresp="#p_MH_1">Maki</persName>. Unable or disinclined resort to Shah’s
                    power dissolve Majlis <persName corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName> struck upon
                    expedient of mass resignation <gloss target="#t_NMF_1">NMF</gloss> [<hi
                        rend="italic">
                        <gloss target="#t_NF_1">NF</gloss>
                    </hi>] deputies and announcement referendum. Latter not provided for in
                    constitution.</p>
                <p>Despite Prime Minister’s decreased popularity he still controls principal
                    propaganda media including Radio Tehran as well as government apparatus and
                    funds with which maneuver balloting or demonstrations his favor. Timing also
                    important factor. By invoking memory July 21 uprising Prime Minister can play
                    upon emotions his followers and upon fear his enemies. While opposition
                    continues display courageous facade it appears incapable combatting <persName
                        corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName> in showdown struggle. It furthermore
                    lacks leadership while Shah continues docile in hands Prime Minister.</p>
                <p>Thus despite almost hopeless financial and economic situation and lack tangible
                    prospects resolving country’s problems in foreseeable future <persName
                        corresp="#p_MM_1">Mosadeq</persName> again demonstrating willingness
                    disregard legalities and determination remain in power regardless of
                    consequences. If he succeeds confirming dissolution Majlis through referendum as
                    now seems probable establishment dictatorship will be complete with little
                    remaining of outward democratic forms. Prime Minister will then be in <pb
                        facs="0674" n="637" xml:id="pg_637"/> position destroy remaining opposition
                    leaving him in unchallenged and absolute control.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_MGH_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_MGH_1">Mattison</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
